      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="content-section">
        <div class="content-label">Common Questions</div>
        <h2 class="content-h2">Frequently Asked <em>Questions</em></h2>
        <div class="faq-list" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">What makes multi-modal pain management better than just taking painkillers?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Oral painkillers treat the perception of pain but do nothing to address the underlying cause — the inflamed nerve, the degenerated joint, the nutritional deficiency. Over time, the dose needs to increase, side effects accumulate, and the patient becomes dependent. Multi-modal management targets the actual source of pain with injections, corrects any contributing deficiencies, and rebuilds function through physiotherapy — providing lasting relief without long-term drug dependency.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">How quickly does pain relief begin after treatment?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">It depends on the treatment used. Nerve blocks and steroid injections often provide relief within 24–72 hours. PRP and regenerative therapies take 2–4 weeks to show full benefit as the healing process develops. Vitamin correction therapy typically shows improvement in nerve-related pain within 2–3 weeks. Most patients notice meaningful improvement after their first session.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">Can pain management help vegetarians with chronic pain?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Yes — and this is one of the most commonly missed diagnoses in India. Vegetarians have no dietary source of Vitamin B12, which is found almost exclusively in animal products. B12 deficiency causes nerve inflammation, neuropathic pain, fatigue, and muscle weakness. Many vegetarian patients with "unexplained" chronic pain are actually suffering from B12 deficiency. Correcting this with injection therapy often produces dramatic, rapid improvement.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">Is pain management available for cancer patients?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Yes. Dr. Sarish Sharma provides targeted musculoskeletal pain management support for oncology patients experiencing bone pain, nerve compression, or joint pain related to their condition or treatment. This is coordinated alongside the patient's primary oncology team. The goal is to maximise quality of life and functional ability during and after cancer treatment.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">Do I need to bring my reports or MRI for a pain management consultation?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Bring any reports you have — they are helpful but not essential. Dr. Sarish Sharma's approach is clinical-first: he diagnoses and creates treatment plans based on your symptoms and physical examination findings. He avoids ordering unnecessary investigations. If additional tests are genuinely needed, he will request them — but many patients receive a complete assessment and treatment plan on their very first visit.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

